# PROFIBUS and PROFINET Frame Formats — In-Depth Detailed Explanation

Understanding frame structure is one of the most important parts of industrial communication engineering because the frame defines:

* How devices identify each other
* How commands are sent
* How data is protected from corruption
* How synchronization happens
* How deterministic communication is achieved

This explanation covers:

1. PROFIBUS frame architecture
2. PROFIBUS telegram types
3. PROFIBUS DP frame structure
4. PROFIBUS token frame
5. PROFIBUS timing and checksum
6. PROFINET Ethernet frame structure
7. RT and IRT frame mechanisms
8. VLAN and priority tagging
9. Ethernet MAC-level operation
10. Real industrial packet behavior

---

# PART 1 — PROFIBUS FRAME FORMAT

# 1. PROFIBUS Communication Fundamentals

PROFIBUS uses:

* RS-485 serial communication
* Byte-oriented telegrams
* Master-slave architecture
* Deterministic polling
* Token passing between masters

Communication occurs through:

> TELEGRAMS (frames)

A telegram is a structured sequence of bytes.

---

# 2. PROFIBUS Telegram Types

PROFIBUS defines several telegram formats.

| SD Value | Telegram Type | Purpose              |
| -------- | ------------- | -------------------- |
| 0x10     | SD1           | Short fixed-length   |
| 0x68     | SD2           | Variable-length      |
| 0xA2     | SD3           | Fixed-length data    |
| 0xDC     | SD4           | Token passing        |
| 0xE5     | SC            | Short acknowledgment |

---

# 3. PROFIBUS General Frame Structure

Typical PROFIBUS frame:

```text
+----+----+----+----+------+----+----+
| SD | LE | DA | SA | DATA | FCS| ED |
+----+----+----+----+------+----+----+
```

Where:

| Field | Meaning              |
| ----- | -------------------- |
| SD    | Start Delimiter      |
| LE    | Length               |
| DA    | Destination Address  |
| SA    | Source Address       |
| DATA  | Payload              |
| FCS   | Frame Check Sequence |
| ED    | End Delimiter        |

---

# 4. PROFIBUS SD2 Frame (Most Important)

The SD2 frame is the most commonly used in PROFIBUS DP cyclic communication.

---

# 4.1 SD2 Detailed Structure

```text
+------+------+------+------+------+------+------+------+
| SD2 | LE   | LEr  | SD2 | DA   | SA   | FC   | DATA |
+------+------+------+------+------+------+------+------+

+------+------+
| FCS  | ED   |
+------+------+
```

---

# 4.2 Byte-by-Byte Explanation

---

## A. SD2 (Start Delimiter)

Value:

```text
68H
```

Purpose:

* Indicates beginning of variable-length frame
* Helps receiver synchronize

Why repeated?

* Improves reliability
* Detects corruption

---

## B. LE (Length)

Specifies:

```text
Number of bytes from DA to FCS
```

Example:

```text
LE = 08H
```

Means:
8 bytes follow.

---

## C. LEr (Repeated Length)

Repeated copy of LE.

Purpose:

* Error checking
* Corruption detection

Receiver compares:

```text
LE == LEr
```

If mismatch:
Frame rejected.

---

## D. DA (Destination Address)

1 byte.

Specifies target device.

Range:

```text
0–125
```

Examples:

| Address | Device    |
| ------- | --------- |
| 2       | PLC       |
| 5       | Drive     |
| 10      | Remote IO |

Broadcast addresses also exist.

---

## E. SA (Source Address)

Address of transmitting device.

Used for:

* Reply routing
* Diagnostics
* Device identification

---

## F. FC (Function Code)

Very important field.

Defines:

* Request type
* Response type
* Data exchange behavior

---

# 4.3 Function Code Breakdown

Example:

```text
FC = 3CH
```

Bit-level meaning:

```text
00111100
```

Contains:

* Frame type
* Request/response
* Acknowledgment
* Data transfer control

---

## Common Functions

| FC Type   | Purpose                    |
| --------- | -------------------------- |
| SDA       | Send Data with Acknowledge |
| SRD       | Send and Request Data      |
| Token     | Token management           |
| Diagnosis | Diagnostic request         |

---

# 4.4 DATA Field

Contains:

* Input/output data
* Parameters
* Diagnostics
* Commands

Size:
Variable.

Example:

```text
DATA = Motor speed, sensor values
```

---

# 4.5 FCS (Frame Check Sequence)

Checksum field.

Used for:

* Error detection

PROFIBUS uses:

```text
Hamming distance protection
```

Calculated over:

```text
DA + SA + FC + DATA
```

Receiver recalculates checksum.

If mismatch:
Frame discarded.

---

# 4.6 ED (End Delimiter)

Fixed value:

```text
16H
```

Marks frame end.

---

# 5. PROFIBUS SD1 Frame

Short acknowledgment/control frame.

Structure:

```text
+----+----+----+----+----+
| SD1| DA | SA | FC | ED |
+----+----+----+----+----+
```

Used when:

* Data payload unnecessary
* Fast control messages needed

---

# 6. PROFIBUS Token Passing Frame (SD4)

Critical in multi-master systems.

---

# 6.1 Token Frame Structure

```text
+----+----+----+----+
| SD4| DA | SA | ED |
+----+----+----+----+
```

---

# 6.2 Working

Example:

```text
Master1 -> Token -> Master2
```

Meaning:
Master2 now owns bus access rights.

This guarantees:

* Collision-free communication
* Deterministic access

---

# 7. PROFIBUS Acknowledgment Frame (SC)

Very short frame.

```text
E5H
```

Single-byte acknowledgment.

Used for:

* Positive ACK

Very fast response.

---

# 8. PROFIBUS Timing Concepts

Critical for deterministic behavior.

---

# 8.1 Tbit

Time for one bit transmission.

Formula:

T_{bit}=\frac{1}{Baud\ Rate}

Example:

At 12 Mbps:

```text
Tbit = 83.3 ns
```

---

# 8.2 Slot Time

Maximum waiting time for response.

If exceeded:

* Retry occurs
* Fault generated

---

# 8.3 Token Rotation Time

Maximum token circulation duration.

Important for:

* Predictable scan cycle

---

# 9. PROFIBUS Example Telegram

Example cyclic output write:

```text
68 08 08 68 05 02 3D 11 22 33 44 A7 16
```

---

# 9.1 Decode

| Byte        | Meaning                |
| ----------- | ---------------------- |
| 68          | Start delimiter        |
| 08          | Length                 |
| 08          | Repeated length        |
| 68          | Start delimiter repeat |
| 05          | Destination            |
| 02          | Source                 |
| 3D          | Function code          |
| 11 22 33 44 | Data                   |
| A7          | Checksum               |
| 16          | End delimiter          |

---

# PART 2 — PROFINET FRAME FORMAT

PROFINET is fundamentally different because it uses Ethernet.

---

# 10. PROFINET Ethernet Architecture

PROFINET frames are Ethernet frames with industrial extensions.

Supports:

* Standard Ethernet
* Real-time Ethernet
* Isochronous communication

---

# 11. Ethernet Frame Basics

PROFINET frame is based on IEEE 802.3 Ethernet.

Basic Ethernet frame:

```text
+------+-----+------+-------+------+------+
| PRE  | MAC | TYPE | DATA  | FCS  | IFG  |
+------+-----+------+-------+------+------+
```

---

# 12. Complete PROFINET RT Frame

```text
+----------+----------+--------+--------+--------+
| Dest MAC | Src MAC  | VLAN   | EtherT | Data   |
+----------+----------+--------+--------+--------+

+--------+
| CRC/FCS|
+--------+
```

---

# 13. Ethernet Field Details

---

## A. Preamble

7 bytes.

Pattern:

```text
10101010
```

Purpose:

* Clock synchronization

---

## B. SFD (Start Frame Delimiter)

1 byte:

```text
10101011
```

Indicates actual frame start.

---

## C. Destination MAC

6 bytes.

Example:

```text
01:0E:CF:00:00:01
```

Can be:

* Unicast
* Multicast
* Broadcast

---

## D. Source MAC

6 bytes.

Unique device hardware address.

---

# 14. VLAN Tag (IEEE 802.1Q)

Important in PROFINET RT/IRT.

Structure:

```text
+------+------+
| TPID | TCI  |
+------+------+
```

---

## 14.1 TPID

Usually:

```text
0x8100
```

Indicates VLAN tagging.

---

## 14.2 TCI Breakdown

Contains:

* Priority
* VLAN ID

---

# 15. Priority Code Point (PCP)

Very important for industrial traffic.

3 bits.

Values:

```text
0–7
```

PROFINET RT often uses:

```text
Priority = 6
```

This ensures switches prioritize automation traffic.

---

# 16. EtherType Field

Identifies protocol.

PROFINET RT EtherType:

```text
0x8892
```

Switch/receiver recognizes:

> This is PROFINET real-time traffic.

---

# 17. PROFINET Data Field

Contains:

```text
+--------+--------+--------+
| FrameID| Status | Payload|
+--------+--------+--------+
```

---

# 18. Frame ID

Identifies communication type.

Examples:

| Frame ID Range | Meaning      |
| -------------- | ------------ |
| 0x8000–0xBBFF  | RT data      |
| 0xFC01         | Alarm        |
| 0xFEFC         | DCP identify |

---

# 19. Status Field

Contains:

* Data validity
* Provider state
* Consumer state

Important for synchronization.

---

# 20. Payload

Actual process data.

Examples:

* Sensor values
* Drive commands
* Encoder position

---

# 21. Ethernet CRC/FCS

32-bit CRC.

Detects:

* Bit errors
* Corrupted frames

Very strong protection.

---

# 22. PROFINET RT Communication

RT bypasses TCP/IP stack.

Normal Ethernet:

```text
Application -> TCP -> IP -> Ethernet
```

PROFINET RT:

```text
Application -> Ethernet directly
```

Result:

* Lower latency
* Faster updates

---

# 23. PROFINET IRT Frame Concept

IRT introduces:

* Time scheduling
* Deterministic Ethernet

---

# 23.1 Time Division

Cycle divided into phases:

```text
| IRT | RT | TCP/IP |
```

---

# 23.2 Example

```text
0–200 us     -> Servo control
200–400 us   -> IO traffic
400–1000 us  -> Standard Ethernet
```

This guarantees deterministic motion control.

---

# 24. DCP Frames

Used for:

* Device discovery
* Naming
* IP assignment

Broadcast Ethernet frames.

---

# 24.1 DCP Identify Request

Engineering tool sends:

```text
Who is device with this name?
```

Device responds with:

* MAC
* Name
* IP

